element.documentation: all instruments are exchange rates

element.documentation: seller

element.name: long [derived]
element.documentation: buyer

element.name: portfolio
element.documentation:
- portfolio is a collection of contracts - A portfolio is a collection of contracts that can be valued as a whole. - Portfolios are commonly formed from a number of properties of contracts, including counterparty, dealer (the primary party), instrument, and dates of the deal
- Portfolios can be transient or persistent.

element.name: portfolio filter
element.documentation: pattern strategy: мы можем выбрать любой фильтр - filter is only used for selection purposes. -We can easily add other portfolio filters. - - This allows us to use the contract selector for simple cases and use a range of hard-coded fiiters for more complex situations.

element.name: contract filter
element.documentation: This allows us to use the contract selector for simple cases

element.name: hard coded filter
element.documentation: use a range of hard-coded fiiters for more complex situations.

element.name: is included (contract)
element.documentation: - Subclasses of the portfolio filter override isIncluded to provide their specific behaviors.

element.name: select contracts (collection of contracts)
element.documentation: - The select operation on the portfolio filter takes a collection of contracts and returns another collection of contracts - For each contract in the input collection, the select operation evaluates isIncluded and, if true, adds it to the result.

element.name: value (scenario)
element.documentation: - позволяет рассчитать ценность всего пакета целиком - в простом случае равен сумме всех входящих контрактов

quote
element.documentation: - котировка - quote is a fundamental type

element.name: bid
element.documentation: - the price to buy (the bid предложение цены)

element.name: offer
element.documentation: - the price to sell (the offer).

element.name: spread
element.documentation: - spread—the difference between the bid and the offer

element.name: scenario
element.documentation: - The scenario represents the state of the market at a certain point in time, and the elements within the scenario represent the prices at that point

element.name: timepoint
element.documentation: We need to be able to show how prices can change over time and to keep a history of those changes

element.name: market indicator
element.documentation: - market indicator as a supertype of instrument. This reflects the fact that scenarios can contain things other than instruments (for example, a market indicator includes volatilities, as well as all instruments)

element.name: sourced scenario element
element.documentation: origins of a price: publication by some body that is widely quoted in the market,

element.name: calculated scenario element
element.documentation: - calculation from other prices or market characteristics - In this case the calculated scenario element has a list of scenario elements as arguments and a formula

element.name: cross rate scenario element
element.documentation: If we know the exchange rates for USD/DEM and for USD/GBP, then we can calculate the exchange rate for GBP/DEM as (USD/DEM) / (USD/GBP).

element.name: information source
element.documentation: Typically these instructions come from a source, such as Reuters, that tells where to look for information (for example, "Page 3, second column of the row starting IBM")

element.name: formula
element.documentation: We can build an interpreter [1] that recognizes a simple range of formulaic expressions. This technique is familiar to any user who has used spreadsheets

relationship.name: N|0 - 1 publisher
relationship.documentation: - We also need to consider markets that do not have a single publisher for a price, such as the foreign exchange market. In such cases we need to add the party that is publishing the price to the model.
